The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic already this year.
Maybe
Perhaps the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer almost all services as their partners in Western Europe.
However, there is something missing – a virtual operator that obligations traditional ones to lower the price.
Maybe it won't be long.
Since Czech operators belong to the most expensive operators in Europe, we have written many times on Mobil.cz.
At the end of the day, ČTú also confirmed that the price of SMS is higher than that of the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the area of regulating roaming tariffs, perhaps a paradoxical situation will be created - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How can prices in the Czech Republic remain so high against Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really want to start the fight.
Maybe it sounds absurd, as well as we have three mobile networks and highly covered over 100 %.
On the other hand, mobile telephony operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this regard, the Head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (ČTú) , Pavel Dvořák , who in the past has said that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with his own network no longer has many possibilities. (However it might be difficult to find other frequencies.)
But there is still another possibility - the virtual operator.
The entry into the market of virtual operators has led to a significant fall in prices, to which traditional operators would have to react.
At the same time, even before sharks such as Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile entered the market, similar voices were echoed in Britain as we do.
However, it has been shown that the place for operators of this kind is there and that can really be successful.
After all, we don't have to go very far.
In February of this year we informed you about the arrival of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this operator managed to conquer more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time behind Mobilking is the Penta financial group to which in the Czech Republic belongs among the other U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete group-braining.
In order to be able to function effectively, that is, many fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They do not go behind, i.e., relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world virtual operators usually present themselves at low cost, offer low-price calls and SMS, which is often in balance with the offer of the most restricted services
So for example Tesco Mobile in Britain offers SMS that cost as little as half as its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be a pretty good move even the bet on a group-brain not recently.
This operator aims to specifically say about men.
"The real men choose Mobilking operator who likes and you can trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company that produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether we can also affirm a similar concept as in Poland.
The press spokesman for Vodafone Miroslav Čepický doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition from the point of view of services, it is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic there is no possibility, say mobile network operators
But it seems almost certain that if there will never be an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic negotiations do not have many expectations.
Mobilking will be on quite a scale in the other countries in our area," he said in a telephone dialogue for Mobile.cz Jana Studničková, the press spokesman for the Penta financial group.
He therefore pointed out that the current operators in the Czech Republic are not clearly in favour of this.
On the contrary, they try to do everything because no competing potential is created.
For some time it has not hidden its own interest in the launch of a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group that would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónika O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And it's better first.
We have repeatedly negotiated on this possibility with all the Czech operators of the mobile network.
We have already been able to progress in negotiations with some of them," says the spokesman of the Pavel Kaidl Group.
So maybe better times are coming.
Unofficial information shows that the first virtual operator will have it by the end of the year.
But for now around its creation there is an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At this moment we do not believe that in the Czech market there is room for the creation of a fully-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no subject with a complex and serious project has been addressed to us," he mentioned in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň of the Telefónika O2 press section.
The specific nature of the Czech market also applies to other operators.
The T-Mobil press spokesman Martina Kemrová adds in a rare agreement with the O2 declaration: "For now we have not noticed any vital and beneficial commercial project for both, on which it is possible to continue to build".
And he adds: "On the T-Mobile network a virtual operator will hardly appear by the end of the year.
At this moment we should have had a concrete agreement on the table, so that it could be considered on the horizon."
Vodafone concentrates its attention rather than reaching its 3G licence requests.
He adds Miroslav Čepický: "We are open to the negotiations of potential virtual operators and this in particular in the context of the sharing of expenditure and infrastructure.
We consider this, from a customer's point of view, the most productive.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet."
The competent authorities -with complicating operators
The attitude of mobile telephone operators can easily be understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices and thus to a decrease in profit.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The disturbances around the creation U:phone testify that when operators hold to something they know how to get back on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure was pressing against ČTú in the period of creation of U:phone to the company of T-Mobile.
This testifies to public access information from ČTú's web pages.
But right now U:fon serves as a topic for which not to accept the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová observed: "The competition environment of the mobile telephony market has been greatly enhanced by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would place on him and above all on his high claims services."
Of the attitude of mobile telephone operators, however, it is quite surprising that the Czech regulators have a complete lack of interest.
It is not only the attitude of the ČTú that unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike Britain and other developed countries - has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
However, this over the whole problem has taken its typical position.
"The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market would be possible after the conclusion of the contract of the rental of the required infrastructure between the mobile operator and the virtual operator had been realized.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers has probably not been quite interesting for traditional operators," said Kristian Chalupa, from the UOHS external relations section, in response to our question.
Such a statement by the representatives of the operators might not surprise.
On the other hand, the office which has to defend the interests of consumers and, above all, to take care of the fact that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, is more than a delicate matter.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Over abroad where virtual operators commonly work, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile telephony services."
But of course the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and lowering prices do not belong to the interests of UOHS.
Truly shocking in all the situation is the almost exciting harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question as to whether it really is just a coincidence is a matter for itself.
Similarly, the same price of petrol for all petrol is undoubtedly the result of coincidence and competitive struggle.
"The section has not found any evidence of anti-competitive behavior regarding this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position, so he has no corresponding responsibility for his behaviour on the market.
The necessary tools for the opening up of the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be missing from the telecommunication regulator," said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points .
Of course there is the analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTú, according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of economic competition the only market.
On such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach - for the creation of a virtual operator, the agreement of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile operator has – at the end of the accounts logically – the monopoly of his network.
So for a certain portion it must be dominant by force.
But even if we do not admit this argument, for UOHS it should be a minimum alarming that three mobile operators proceed so strangely similar.
At the same time, complaints from interested parties (including the mentioned GTS Novera company) show that during negotiations with all operators encounter very similar obstacles.
Downloading responsibility to ČTú in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which UOHS is kept out of the whole matter.
This has already been found in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not possible to promote the expansion of the rights of ČTú in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the recently approved telecommunications law was updated, despite the fact that many experts were expecting the improvement of the situation from this point of view.
This is what UOHS representatives need to know more about, but perhaps their interests are elsewhere.
You can do it, when no one looks
While we are unaware of the operation of these pseudo-virtual operators, some of them even exist in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their own price lists of mobile telephony services but are only partially public.
These are usually multilevel marketing companies.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only the pre-established persons.
The magic is that the company appears as a classic business customer, who orders a large amount of SIM card.
As an important customer then receives special price offers (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a provision.
"If the cases referred to in this article were presented, of which we will be interested, there could be a breach of contractual conditions, and it could result in the conclusion of cooperation with that company," she replied to the question Martina Kemrová.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity would not reach the ears of those responsible for mobile telephony operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, this can be thousands of customers.
No operator defends himself at the same time from such an attitude.
From the activities of these companies, that is to say, they make a profit that is not indifferent and at the same time - unlike the actual virtual operators - they are not harmed in any way by their official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns about possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however only a negligible percentage of customers uses the services of these companies.
These must also accept that the SIM card on their phone is not registered on their behalf, so they cannot have it in full as the usual customers of mobile phone operators "
But this should be a little strange to the ČTú.
In addition, another issue for UOHS is opened.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an attitude, why do they block the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that UOHS has strong enough rights to expose similar activities and if you do not want to, you will not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the operators who have no idea of all this and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When We're No Longer Costs
As has already been said many times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile phone market has led to a significant fall in prices for services.
At the same time in virtually all countries where operators were born, traditional operators tried to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were almost identical - too small market, at the limit too saturated, problems with the quality of services etc.
But in the developed countries in these cases, the defence regulators have intervened not by mobile phone operators but by their customers.
Both with the formal measures and with the non-formal pressure, then came to the creation of the first virtual operator and to him have helped others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators launch from one another all the time as a boiling potato.
For our experience we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of competence in these cases makes it more than comfortable.
But we don't throw the sponge.
If the backstage information is right and the virtual operator will appear really soon from us, the Czech mobile phone market will be moved back.
If one of the operators consented to the creation of a virtual mobile operator only UOHS could be impatiable to the refusal (discrimination) of the other parties concerned.
And we may stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech enno has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to the four new versions of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek, on the occasion of the day of the recognition of the Czech State, solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem "Kde kaslav m'j".
The new recording of the anno was made by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available – solo with male or female voice, chorus step and instrumental edition.
The song is under the direction of Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the anno's revisions are Otakar Jeremiaš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz site you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song one of the most beautiful hymns.
Earlier he told the radio "Český rozhlas" that he chose specifically to sing the variants alone, the singers with the most representative young voices, which are expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I tried to take care that both the chorus and the chorus, have the clear dictionary, that the text is well understood, that they are in harmony," he said.
Then the national anthem will celebrate next year the 175th anniversary.
The song "Kde kaslav m'j" was played for the first time in 1834 on stage of the Stavovskéh divadlo in the original work Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl accompanied by music by František Škroupa.
He acquired popularity and people spontaneously made it his own.
The first verse of the song after the foundation of Czechoslovakia in 1918 became the natural part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the birth of the autonomous Czech Republic.
