The Ministry of the Interior requires drivers with three administrative sanctions for excessive blood alcohol, to install in their car the system that prevents driving the vehicle in a state of roughness or if it does not blow up the device.
The measure was announced last June and is already included in the annual report of the Attorney-General's Office, according to which it will be a one-year pilot project.
The purpose of this project is to reintegrate the driver, since this will have to attend a rehabilitation course on the road.
This initiative, in addition to the Public Prosecutor's Office for Road Safety, will participate in the Directorate-General for Traffic (DGT) and the Institute of Technology for Automobile Safety (FITSA).
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of the reported cars reported more than once for driving in a state of ebb then goes back to driving the car.
Alcohol will avoid it, because it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the rate of alcohol in the breathed air and prevents the motor vehicle from being moved if the driver does not blow, or when a higher alcohol concentration is detected than that permitted.
The cost is higher than 1000 euros and would be borne by the sanctioned person.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with these devices allow to reduce up to 65% of the infringements committed during the first year of introduction.
And in Spain it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people a year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to stop these behaviours before they become criminal offences.
And to facilitate its development, since legal reform can be carried out on a regular basis, and, no doubt, the necessary reform for the criminal procedure would require an organic law.
However, the device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial solution, although it has already been introduced in experimentally in some industrial and public vehicles.
