Talk in the sleep
Some kids talk during the night.
I am not referring to those who wake up who are very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the day before, but to those children who are talking about being asleep.
The first time it happens, at most it's scary, but it's not really very important.
This is a benign alteration of sleep called sleep talk.
It occurs at a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Of course, most of you told that you had spoken in your sleep.
This may occur in a very sporadic way (once in life, for example associated with a high fever episode) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single reason to explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes there are episodes related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night fears, night enuresis (do pee in bed), or sleepwalking, but not necessarily so.
As mentioned above, it can be associated with very high fever stages, stress situations or overcrowding.
In any case, it is still a poorly studied phenomenon.
Even the intensity with which it appears is extremely variable.
It may happen that the person speaks with a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite occurs (scream, shout, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be appropriate to observe the child and perhaps consult a specialist to check whether there is any question that is causing an abnormal state of anxiety as a blur from the situation.
We said that this is a benign alteration, so there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, if associated with insomnia or stress).
What can be done, on the other hand, is to consider a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before I go to sleep.
Offer quiet games and avoid TV programs or series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for which it is difficult to relax, relaxing techniques can be used to help them gain some inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more quietly.
Once sleepwalkers appear, try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless for the child and that the next day he will remember nothing of what happened.
Useful advice
