The meeting - Blood is safe again
Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday the tenth anniversary of his foundation, and his president, Dr. FrancineDécary, had every reason to rejoice, since Hema-Québec became one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
And above all, he regained the confidence of the public, seriously shocked by the scandal of the infected blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
In the face of such a tragedy and the protests of the population, the Government of Canada conducted a public investigation in February 1994 , directed by Judge Horace Krever , which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent the recurrence of such disaster.
While Judge Krever delayed to draw up a report, some provinces set up a committee with the aim of designing a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Hema-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and two territories.
In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, just 38% of the people said they still had confidence in the donation system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was deadly.
Thanks to continuous efforts to improve the safety of blood samples and field research over the following years, we have regained public confidence," he says before saying proud that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the population of Quebec now had confidence in Hema-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary is convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases in Europe of the human variant of the mad cow, a new manifestation of the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, told by the president since 1998, the year of the foundation.
"And we didn't fully know if that disease could be transmitted by infected blood.
We have therefore based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, according to which, when you have doubts and could achieve a serious illness, in this case, the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, take measures of exclusion.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than one month in the United Kingdom was refused from 1980 onwards.
Now, for some years, it has been shown that this disease is undoubtedly transmitted by infected blood.
This episode has thus shown us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999 a much more efficient technique for the identification of HIV appeared on the market: the tests of nucleic acid (TAN) that allow the presence of the virus and not of antibodies against the virus directly in the blood of donors, on which the tests used until then were based.
TAN have allowed to reduce the window period, or since the person has contracted the disease to the one where the first viruses can be identified in the blood thanks to our techniques, the specialist explains.
That period could be reduced to a period of less than one week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and therefore not being able to identify them has decreased significantly.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving blood infected with the HIV virus.
"In other words, this means that 12 million blood samples will need to be distributed before someone gets infected with the HIV virus.
Since Hema-Québec distributes every year between 400 000 and 500 000 blood samples, it will take more than 24 years before there is a case of HIV transmitted with a transfusion.
I believe that today you can feel calm in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover your health, says the head of the management of Hema-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than a year ago, the Chikungunya virus, like the West Nile virus, appeared on Réunion Island, was transmitted into the blood by an insect.
It is necessary to be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary before stressing that, in addition to having safe resources, Hema-Québec must also provide sufficient supplies.
"Needs increase as the population grows older.
As treatment against more aggressive cancer, patients often need a red blood cell or platelet intake.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the number of donors who on average constitute only 3% of Quebec's inhabitants acceptable as donors."
All healthy people who have reached the age of 18 years and meet the eligibility criteria may, however, donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of the people who offer themselves as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where the latter is widespread, they will be refused for a period of one year.
"With this 3% we can maintain an inventory capable of responding to the needs of hospitals.
The cases of shortage are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this group of donors as they age and can no longer make donations.
Now it is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to hold them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Today life is so frenzy that it is hardly an hour to donate blood," says the desolate Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec distributes not only blood samples, but also human tissues, of which bone transplants, eyeball heart valves and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe wear.
These fabrics are analysed, processed and frozen before being deposited with the Hema-Québec that manages the only public bank of umbilical cord blood in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, abundant blood rich in stem cells that can serve to cure serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the entry into the bank of our thousandth blood sample of cordon and we plan to take more than a thousand of them every year.
You should start to propose them for transplants at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Décary who describes this practice of cordon blood removal as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot have access to you," because Hema-Québec does not have the means to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
