Mp3 readers under charge, put the hearing at risk
Listening to high-volume music for a prolonged period of time using portable musical devices such as Mp3 readers can cause permanent hearing injuries.
It is as the European Commission points out, that in a statement published in Brussels, it cites the opinion of the Scientific Committee on Emerging Health Risks and recently identified (Cssseri) of the EU, published today.
"From this scientific opinion - it is read in the note - it emerges that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable musical devices weekly for more than an hour a day holding the high volume device risk a permanent loss of hearing ability."
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable musical devices and mobile phones at high sound levels can unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably," says Meglena Kuneva.
"From scientific findings - the responsible EU continues - there is a clear risk and we must react quickly.
What matters most, we need to raise awareness of consumers and make this information public.
We must also review existing control systems, in the light of this scientific opinion, to ensure that they are fully effective and take the step with the new technology."
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the widespread use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise from them.
"Scientists - the EU executive concludes - confirm that there is cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine with the Member States and interested parties what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from noise exposure from portable musical devices and related equipment."
At present, there is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical equipment to 100 dB, but concerns about hearing damage that can result from excessive exposure to such noise sources are growing.
It is possible to limit these damage by using solutions such as reduction of levels and duration of noise exposure.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee notes that users of portable musical equipment are listening to music at a high volume (more than 89 decibels) for only 5 hours per week, exceeding the currently in force limits on maximum noise at the workplace.
Those who listen to music in these conditions for longer periods risk a permanent loss of hearing ability after a period of 5 years.
This would cover 5-10% of users of these devices and their number can be quantified between 2.5 million and 10 million people in the EU.
